<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-IV-1-sols">
        <title><m>\S IV.1</m>: Sequences</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: Sequences  </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Sequences are important structures used in programming, and we use functions to define
                            them. We'll look at the basics of building sequences in this section.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Definition: Sequence</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            A <term>sequence</term> is a 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            function <m>a: \N_0 \to \R</m> (or <m>a: \N \to \R</m>).
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since our domain is <m>\N_0</m>, it is common to imagine sequences as an infinite ordered
                            list:
                            <me>
                                a(0), a(1), a(2), \dots
                            </me>
                            which is more commonly written as 
                            <me>
                                (a_i)_{i \in \N_0} = (a_i) = a_0, a_1, a_2, \dots
                            </me>.
                            
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Examples: Sequences</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            There are various ways we can define sequences, but a common way is with an explicit function.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The sequence <m>(a_i), a_i = i^2 + 1</m> is the sequence
                            <me>
                                (a_i) = 1,2,5,10,\dots
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The sequence <m>(b_n), b_n = \frac{1}{n!}</m> is the sequence
                            <me>
                                (b_n) = 1,1,\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{6}, \dots
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Sequences</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write out the first <m>5</m> terms of each sequence below.
                                <ol>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(a_j), a_j = 2^j + j</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(b_i), b_i = \frac{i+1}{i!}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <ol>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(a_j) = 1,3,6,11,20,\dots</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(b_i) = 1,2, \frac{3}{2}, \frac{4}{6}, \frac{5}{24},\dots</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                What is a possible rule for the sequence
                                <me>
                                    (c_n) = \frac{1}{2}, \frac{2}{3}, \frac{3}{4}, \dots
                                </me>
                                
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                A possible rule is <m>c_n = \frac{n+1}{n+2}</m>. Another possible rule is 
                                <m>c_n = \frac{-1}{24}n^2 + \frac{5}{24}n + \frac{1}{2}</m>. In general, there are many
                                rules that satisfy finitely many points, so this is not a good way to communicate a sequence.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Observations: Sequences</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        It can often be useful to visualizes sequences. Graphs of sequences are 
                                        discrete points in the coordinate plane.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Sequences are functions, so they can be combined in natural ways. Given two
                                        sequences <m>(a_i)</m> and <m>(b_i)</m>, we can form new sequences:
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    <m>(a_i + b_i)</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    <m>(a_i - b_i)</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    <m>(a_i \cdot b_i)</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    <m>(a_i / b_i)</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ol>
                                        We generally do not compose two sequences (why not?).
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

        </worksheet>
    </article>
